02:44.720 --> 02:48.480
You played a serial killer in the movie Seven.

02:48.480 --> 02:55.320
Your performance was one of, if not the greatest portrayal of a murderer on screen ever.

02:55.320 --> 02:57.560
What was your process of becoming him?

02:57.560 --> 03:00.080
John Doe, the serial killer.

03:00.080 --> 03:04.960
The truth is, I didn't get the part.

03:04.960 --> 03:11.600
I had been in Los Angeles making a couple of films, Swimming of Sharks and Usual Suspects.

03:11.600 --> 03:18.160
And then I did a film called Outbreak that Morgan Freeman was in.

03:18.160 --> 03:29.800
And I went in to audition for David Fincher in probably late November of 94.

03:29.800 --> 03:34.080
And I auditioned for this part and didn't get it.

03:34.080 --> 03:37.360
And I went back to New York.

03:37.360 --> 03:43.960
And I think they started shooting like December 12th.

03:43.960 --> 03:44.960
And I'm in New York.

03:44.960 --> 03:50.120
I'm back in my wonderful apartment on West 12th Street, and my mom has come to visit

03:50.120 --> 03:51.680
for Christmas.

03:51.680 --> 03:54.440
And it's December 23rd.

03:54.440 --> 03:59.040
And it's like seven o'clock at night, and my phone rings.

03:59.040 --> 04:03.880
And it's Arnold Copelson, who's the producer of Seven.

04:03.880 --> 04:07.840
And he's very jovial, and he's very friendly, and he says, how are you doing?

04:07.840 --> 04:08.840
And I said, fine.

04:08.840 --> 04:12.520
And he said, listen, do you remember that film you came in for, Seven?

04:12.520 --> 04:14.040
And I said, yeah, yeah, absolutely.

04:14.040 --> 04:20.280
He goes, well, it turns out that we hired an actor and we started shooting.

04:20.280 --> 04:24.440
And then yesterday, David fired him.

04:24.440 --> 04:29.360
And David would like you to get on a plane on Sunday and come to Los Angeles and start

04:29.360 --> 04:32.560
shooting on Tuesday.

04:32.560 --> 04:41.520
And I was like, OK, would it be imposing to say, can I read it again?

04:41.520 --> 04:45.640
Because it's been a while now, and I'd like to.

04:45.640 --> 04:49.040
So they sent a script over.

04:49.040 --> 04:51.960
I read the script that night.

04:51.960 --> 04:56.680
I thought about it.

04:56.680 --> 05:00.040
And I had this feeling.

05:00.040 --> 05:09.840
I can't even quite describe it, but I had this feeling that it would be really good

05:09.840 --> 05:14.480
if I didn't take billing in the film.

05:14.480 --> 05:18.560
And the reason I felt that was because I knew that by the time this film would come out,

05:18.560 --> 05:24.360
it would be the last one of the three movies that I just shot, the fourth one.

05:24.360 --> 05:29.880
And if any of those films broke through or did well, if it was going to be Brad Pitt

05:29.880 --> 05:34.280
and Morgan Freeman, Gwyneth Paltrow and Kevin Spacey, and you don't show up for the first

05:34.280 --> 05:38.560
25, 30, 40 minutes, people are going to figure out who you're playing.

05:38.560 --> 05:45.600
So people should know that you play the serial killer in the movie and the serial killer

05:45.600 --> 05:49.120
shows up more than halfway through the movie.

05:49.120 --> 05:50.120
Very late in the movie.

05:50.120 --> 05:55.320
And when you say billing, it's like the posters, the VHS cover and everything.

05:55.320 --> 05:56.320
You're gone.

05:56.320 --> 05:57.320
You're not there.

05:57.320 --> 05:58.320
Not there.

05:58.320 --> 06:04.480
The Green Line Cinema told me to go fuck myself, that they absolutely could use my picture

06:04.480 --> 06:06.400
and my image and all that.

06:06.400 --> 06:12.120
And this became a little bit of a, I'd say, 24-hour conversation.

06:12.120 --> 06:16.840
And it was Fincher who said, I actually think this is a really cool idea.

06:16.840 --> 06:24.840
So the compromise was, I'm the first credit at the end of the movie when the credits start.

06:24.840 --> 06:31.800
So I got on a plane on that Sunday and I flew to Los Angeles and I went into where they

06:31.800 --> 06:36.320
were shooting and I went into the makeup room and David Fincher was there and we were talking

06:36.320 --> 06:44.360
about what should I do, how should I look and I just had my hair short for outbreak

06:44.360 --> 06:51.520
because I was playing a military character and I just looked at the hairdresser and I

06:51.520 --> 06:53.160
said, do you have a razor?

06:53.160 --> 06:55.800
And Fincher went, are you kidding?

06:55.800 --> 06:58.200
And I said, no.

06:58.200 --> 07:02.440
He goes, if you shave your head, I'll shave mine.

07:02.440 --> 07:06.160
So we both shaved our heads.

07:06.160 --> 07:09.440
And then I started shooting the next day.

07:09.440 --> 07:17.600
So my long-winded answer to your question is that I didn't have that much time to think

07:17.600 --> 07:22.120
about how to build that character.

07:22.120 --> 07:33.120
What I think in the end Fincher was able to do so brilliantly with such terror was to set

07:33.120 --> 07:37.760
the audience up to meet this character.

07:37.760 --> 07:44.400
I think the last scene, the ending scene and the car ride leading up to it where it's mostly

07:44.400 --> 07:51.800
on you in conversation with Morgan Freeman and Brad Pitt is one of the greatest scenes

07:51.800 --> 07:53.680
in film history.

07:53.680 --> 07:56.080
So people somehow didn't see the movie.

07:56.080 --> 08:01.120
There's these five murders that happen that are inspired by five of the seven deadly sins

08:01.120 --> 08:07.960
and the ending scene is inspired, represents the last two deadly sins.

08:07.960 --> 08:16.200
And there's this calm subtlety about you and your performance is just terrifying.

08:16.200 --> 08:24.080
Maybe in contrast with Brad Pitt's performance, that's also really strong, but in the contrast

08:24.080 --> 08:30.280
is the terrifying sense that you get in the audience that builds up to the twist at the

08:30.280 --> 08:36.720
end or the surprise at the end with the famous What's in the Box from Brad Pitt.

08:37.120 --> 08:41.240
Brad Pitt's character's wife, her head.

08:41.240 --> 08:42.240
Yeah.

08:42.240 --> 08:47.880
I can really only tell you that while we were shooting that scene in the car, while we were

08:47.880 --> 08:55.640
out in the desert in that place where all those electrical wires were, David just kept

08:55.640 --> 09:01.520
saying less, do less.

09:01.520 --> 09:10.240
And I just tried to, I mean, I remember he kept saying to me, remember, you're in control.

09:10.240 --> 09:13.800
Like you're going to win.

09:13.800 --> 09:20.040
And knowing that should allow you to have tremendous confidence.

09:20.040 --> 09:30.760
And I just followed that lead and I just think it's the kind of film that so many of

09:30.760 --> 09:37.320
the elements that had been at work from the beginning of the movie, in terms of its style,

09:37.320 --> 09:42.680
in terms of how he built this terror, in terms of how he built for the audience a sense of

09:42.680 --> 09:50.360
this person being one of the scariest people they might ever encounter, it really allowed

09:50.360 --> 09:58.760
me to be able to not have to do that much, just say the words and mean them.

09:58.760 --> 10:13.000
And I think it also is, it's an example of what makes tragedy so difficult.

10:13.000 --> 10:18.960
I mean, very often tragedy is people operating without enough information.

10:18.960 --> 10:22.000
They don't have all the facts, Romeo and Juliet.

10:22.000 --> 10:23.000
They don't have all the facts.

10:23.000 --> 10:28.520
They don't know what we know as an audience.

10:29.040 --> 10:40.200
So in the end, whether Brad Pitt's character ends up shooting John Doe or turning the gun

10:40.200 --> 10:45.400
on himself, which was a discussion, I mean, there were a number of alternative endings

10:45.400 --> 10:49.360
that were discussed.

10:49.360 --> 10:52.960
Nothing ends up being tied up in a nice little bow.

10:52.960 --> 11:03.840
It is complicated and shows how nobody wins in the end when you're not operating with

11:03.840 --> 11:05.280
all the information.

11:05.280 --> 11:16.200
When you say, say the words and mean them, what does mean them mean?

11:16.200 --> 11:25.840
I've been very fortunate to be directed by Fincher a couple of times and he would say

11:25.840 --> 11:33.440
to me sometimes, I don't believe a thing that is coming out of your mouth.

11:33.440 --> 11:37.320
Shall we try it again?

11:37.320 --> 11:43.040
And you go, okay, yeah, we can try it again.

11:43.040 --> 11:54.520
And sometimes he'll do take and then you'll look to see if he has any added genius to hand

11:54.520 --> 11:55.520
you.

11:55.520 --> 11:58.760
And he just goes, let's do it again and then let's do it again.

11:58.760 --> 12:03.960
And sometimes I say this in all humility.

12:03.960 --> 12:09.120
He's literally trying to beat the acting out of you.

12:09.120 --> 12:12.920
And by continually saying, do it again, do it again, do it again, and not giving you

12:12.920 --> 12:26.120
any specifics, he is systematically shredding you of all pretense of all, because look,

12:26.120 --> 12:30.120
very often, you know, actors would come in on the set and we've thought about the scene

12:30.120 --> 12:33.480
and we've worked out, you know, I've got this prop and I'm gonna do this thing with a can

12:33.480 --> 12:38.800
and you know, all these things, all the tea, I'm gonna do a thing with that thing.

12:38.800 --> 12:44.680
And David is the kind of director where he just wants you to stop adding all that crap

12:44.680 --> 12:50.880
and just say the words and say them quickly and mean them.

12:50.880 --> 12:54.560
And it takes a while to get to that place.

12:54.560 --> 12:56.200
I'll tell you a story.

12:56.200 --> 13:02.120
This is a story I just love because it's in the exactly the same wheelhouse.

13:02.120 --> 13:06.800
So Jack Lemmon's first movie was a film called It Should Happen to You and it was directed

13:06.800 --> 13:08.040
by George Kuecher.

13:08.040 --> 13:13.120
And Jack tells the story and it was just an incredibly charming story to hear Jack tell.

13:13.120 --> 13:18.760
He said, so I'm doing his picture and let me tell you, this is a terrific part for me

13:18.760 --> 13:19.840
and I'm doing a scene.

13:19.840 --> 13:20.840
It's on my first day.

13:20.840 --> 13:23.080
It's in my first day and it's a terrific scene.

13:23.080 --> 13:27.320
And he goes, we do the first take and George Kuecher comes up to me and he says, Jack,

13:27.320 --> 13:31.120
I said, yeah, he said, could you do, let's do another one, but just do a little less

13:31.120 --> 13:32.120
in this one.

13:32.120 --> 13:35.040
And Jack said, a little less, a little less than what I just did.

13:35.040 --> 13:36.320
He said, yeah, just a little less.

13:36.320 --> 13:39.440
So he goes, we do another take and I think, boy, that was it.

13:39.440 --> 13:41.400
I mean, let's just go home.

13:41.400 --> 13:44.360
And Kuecher walked up to him and said, Jack, let's do another one.

13:44.360 --> 13:47.000
This time just a little bit less.

13:47.000 --> 13:50.280
And Jack said, less than what I just did now.

13:50.280 --> 13:51.520
He said, yeah, just a little bit less.

13:51.520 --> 13:52.520
He goes, oh, okay.

13:52.520 --> 13:56.240
So he did another take and Kuecher came up and he said, Jack, just a little bit less.

13:56.240 --> 13:59.200
And Jack said, a little less than what I just did.

13:59.200 --> 14:00.200
He said, yes.

14:00.200 --> 14:02.200
He said, well, if I do any less, I'm not going to be acting.

14:02.600 --> 14:06.080
And Kuecher said, exactly, Jack, exactly.

14:06.840 --> 14:12.520
I mean, I guess what you're saying is it's extremely difficult to get to the bottom

14:12.520 --> 14:19.240
of a little less because the power, if we just stick even on seven of your

14:19.240 --> 14:21.920
performance is in the tiniest of subtleties.

14:22.160 --> 14:27.000
Like when you say, oh, you didn't know, and you turn your head a little bit and

14:27.000 --> 14:35.280
a little bit like the little bit, maybe a glimmer of a smile appears in your face.

14:35.280 --> 14:36.240
That's subtlety.

14:36.440 --> 14:37.280
That's less.

14:37.880 --> 14:39.840
That's hard to get to, I suppose.

14:40.040 --> 14:40.360
Yeah.

14:40.960 --> 14:48.560
And also because I so well remember, I think the work that Brad did and also

14:48.560 --> 14:52.160
Morgan did in that scene, but the work that Brad had to do, where he had to go.

14:52.920 --> 14:56.480
I remember rehearsing with him as we were all staying at this little hotel

14:56.480 --> 14:57.600
nearby that location.

14:57.600 --> 15:00.440
And we rehearsed the night before we started shooting that sequence.

15:00.440 --> 15:09.360
And I just, I mean, it was just incredible to see the levels of emotions he had to go

15:09.360 --> 15:13.800
through and then the decision of what do I do?

15:15.240 --> 15:17.760
Because if I do what he wants me to do, then he wins.

15:17.760 --> 15:21.160
But if I don't do it, then I'm, what kind of a man, husband am I?

15:22.360 --> 15:24.840
I just thought he did really incredible work.

15:24.920 --> 15:33.120
So it was also not easy to not react to the power of what he was throwing at me.

15:34.520 --> 15:39.200
I just thought it was an extraordinary, a really extraordinary scene.

15:39.480 --> 15:41.040
So what's it like being in that scene?

15:41.040 --> 15:47.440
So it's you, Brad Pitt, Morgan Freeman and Brad Pitt is going over the top, just having

15:47.440 --> 15:53.800
a mental breakdown and is weighing these extremely difficult moral choices, as you're

15:53.800 --> 16:01.480
saying, but he's like screaming and in pain and tormented while you're very subtly smiling.

16:02.600 --> 16:06.680
In terms of the writing and in terms of what the characters had to do is it was an

16:06.680 --> 16:15.520
incredible culmination of how this character could manipulate in the way that he did.

16:15.840 --> 16:20.840
And, and in the end, succeed.

