16:50.120 --> 16:52.280
He's timing how long a scene is taking.

16:53.200 --> 16:58.320
And then he'll say, you need to take a minute off this scene.

17:00.240 --> 17:02.560
Like a minute, yeah, a minute off this scene.

17:03.200 --> 17:04.920
I want it to move like this.

17:05.400 --> 17:06.360
So let's pick it up.

17:06.400 --> 17:07.280
Let's pick up the pace.

17:07.520 --> 17:09.320
Let's take, let's see if we can take a minute off.

17:09.920 --> 17:10.640
Why the speed?

17:10.640 --> 17:13.600
Why, why say it fast is the important thing for him, you think?

17:16.720 --> 17:18.960
I think because Fincher hates indulgence.

17:21.040 --> 17:27.240
And he wants, he wants people to talk the way they do in life, which is, you know, we

17:27.240 --> 17:34.560
don't take big dramatic pauses, you know, before we speak, we speak, we say what we want.

17:34.560 --> 17:35.200
We, you know.

17:36.040 --> 17:40.840
And I guess actors like the dramatic pauses and the, the, the indulge in the dramatic

17:40.840 --> 17:40.880
pauses.

17:40.880 --> 17:42.520
They didn't always like the dramatic pauses.

17:42.520 --> 17:46.800
I mean, look, you didn't want to, you go back any student of acting, you go back to

17:46.800 --> 17:49.320
the 30s and the 40s, 50s.

17:51.000 --> 17:57.920
The speed at which actors spoke, not just in the comedies, which of course, you know,

17:57.920 --> 18:02.520
you look at any Preston Sturges movie and it's incredible how fast people are talking

18:02.520 --> 18:07.440
and how, and how funny things are when they happen that fast.

18:09.280 --> 18:12.360
But then, you know, acting styles changed.

18:12.360 --> 18:19.160
We got into a different kind of thing in the late fifties and sixties and, and, you know,

18:19.200 --> 18:25.240
a lot of actors are feeling it, which is, I'm not saying it's, it's a, it's a bad thing.

18:25.240 --> 18:34.360
It's just that if you want to keep an audience engaged as Fincher does, and I believe

18:34.400 --> 18:47.520
successfully does in all of his work, pace, timing, movement, clarity, speed are admirable

18:48.160 --> 18:48.840
to achieve.

18:49.440 --> 18:53.920
And all of that, he wants the actor to be as natural as possible, to strip away all

18:53.920 --> 18:57.920
the bullshit of acting and become human.

18:58.360 --> 19:00.200
Look, I've been lucky with other directors.

19:00.200 --> 19:01.760
Sam Mendes is similar.

19:02.240 --> 19:06.240
I remember when I walked in to maybe the first rehearsal for Richard, the third that

19:06.240 --> 19:14.240
we were doing, I had brought with me a canopy of, of ailments that my Richard was

19:14.240 --> 19:21.640
going to suffer from, and Sam, you know, eventually whittled it down to like three,

19:21.640 --> 19:25.120
like maybe your arm and maybe thing, and maybe your leg.

19:25.320 --> 19:29.480
But let's get rid of the other 10 things that you brought into the room because I was,

19:29.480 --> 19:32.880
you know, I was so excited to, you know, capture this character.

19:32.880 --> 19:39.480
So, you know, very often, Trevor, known as this way, a lot, a lot of wonderful directors

19:39.520 --> 19:45.120
I've worked with, they're really good at helping you trim and edit.

19:46.280 --> 19:52.440
David Fincher said about you, he's talking in general, I think, but also specifically

19:52.440 --> 19:57.760
in the moment of House of Cards said that you have exceptional skill both as an actor

19:57.800 --> 20:02.480
and as a performer, which he says are different things.

20:02.760 --> 20:06.920
So he defines the former as dramatization of a text and the latter as the

20:06.960 --> 20:08.400
seduction of an audience.

20:09.600 --> 20:14.320
Do you see wisdom in that distinction?

20:14.400 --> 20:19.840
And what does it take to do both the dramatization of a text and the seduction of an audience?

20:20.880 --> 20:23.160
Those are two very interesting descriptions.

20:25.120 --> 20:32.080
When I think, I guess when I think performer, I tend to think entertaining.

20:32.080 --> 20:35.040
I tend to think, I tend to think comedy.

20:35.040 --> 20:36.840
I tend to think winning over an audience.

20:36.840 --> 20:48.160
I tend to think that there's something about that quality of wanting to have people enjoy

20:48.160 --> 20:49.160
themselves.

20:51.360 --> 21:01.000
And when you saddle that against what maybe he means as an actor, which is more dramatic

21:01.000 --> 21:13.080
or more text driven, more, look, I've always believed that my job, not every actor feels

21:13.080 --> 21:17.120
this way, but my job, the way that I've looked at it is that my job is to serve the writing.

21:19.720 --> 21:26.520
And that if I serve the writing, I will in a sense serve myself because I'll be in the

21:26.520 --> 21:30.280
right world, I'll be in the right context, I'll be in the right style.

21:31.000 --> 21:37.080
I'll have embraced what a director's, you know, it's not my painting.

21:37.080 --> 21:38.240
It's someone else's painting.

21:38.240 --> 21:40.440
I'm a series of colors and someone else's painting.

21:41.600 --> 21:52.440
And the barometer for me has always been that when people stop me and talk to me about a

21:52.440 --> 22:00.360
character I've played and reference their name as if they actually exist, that's when I feel

22:00.360 --> 22:02.120
like I've gotten close to doing my job.

22:03.880 --> 22:09.000
Yeah, one of the challenges for me in this conversation is remembering that your name is

22:09.000 --> 22:18.360
Kevin, not Frank or John or any of these characters because they live deeply in the psyche.

22:18.440 --> 22:26.680
To me, that's the greatest compliment for me as an actor.

22:29.000 --> 22:30.840
I love being able to go.

22:30.840 --> 22:39.960
I mean, when I think about performers who inspire me and I remember when I was young

22:39.960 --> 22:46.040
and I was introduced to Spencer Tracey, Henry Fonda, Catherine Hepburn,

22:47.080 --> 22:48.680
I just, I believed who they were.

22:48.680 --> 22:49.720
I knew nothing about them.

22:49.720 --> 22:54.600
They were just these extraordinary characters doing this extraordinary stuff.

22:55.160 --> 23:04.600
And then I think more recently contemporary when I think of the work that Philip Seymour

23:04.600 --> 23:11.960
Hoffman did and Heath Ledger and people that when I think about what they could be doing,

23:11.960 --> 23:16.200
what they could do, what they would have done had they stayed with us.

23:18.440 --> 23:25.480
I'm so excited when I go into a cinema or I go into a play and I completely am taken

23:26.360 --> 23:32.840
to some place that I believe exists and characters that become real.

23:32.840 --> 23:36.920
And those characters become lifelong companions.

23:36.920 --> 23:41.800
Like for me, they travel with you and even if it's the darkest aspects of human nature,

23:41.800 --> 23:42.520
they're always there.

23:44.760 --> 23:51.720
I feel like I almost met them and gotten to know them and gotten to become friends with them almost,

23:51.720 --> 23:54.280
Hannibal Lecter or Forrest Gump.

23:55.240 --> 23:59.080
I mean, I feel like I'm like best friends with Forrest Gump.

23:59.080 --> 24:03.080
I know the guy and I guess he's played by some guy named Tom,

24:03.080 --> 24:05.400
but like Forrest Gump is the guy I'm friends with.

24:07.080 --> 24:10.760
And I think everybody feels like that when they're in the audience with great characters.

24:10.760 --> 24:16.680
They just kind of, they become part of you in some way, the good, the bad and the ugly of them.

24:18.040 --> 24:27.000
One of the things that I feel that I try to do in my work is when I read something for the first

24:27.000 --> 24:37.160
time, when I read a script or play, and I am absolutely devastated by it.

24:37.160 --> 24:43.800
It is, it is the most extraordinary, the most beautiful, the most life affirming or terrifying.

24:46.120 --> 24:54.440
It's then a process weirdly of working backwards because I want to work in such a way that

24:54.440 --> 24:57.720
that's the experience I give to the audience when they first see it,

24:58.600 --> 25:02.200
that they have the experience I had when I read it.

25:03.720 --> 25:06.520
I remember that there's been times in the creative process when

25:08.280 --> 25:11.960
something was pointed out to me or something was, I remember I was doing a play

25:12.680 --> 25:19.080
and I was having this really tough time with one of the last scenes in the play and I just

25:19.080 --> 25:23.720
couldn't figure it out. I was in rehearsal and although we had a director in that play,

25:23.800 --> 25:27.800
I called another friend of mine who was also a director and I had him come over and I said,

25:27.800 --> 25:32.920
look, this scene, I'm just having the toughest. I cannot seem to crack this scene.

25:33.960 --> 25:38.680
We read it through a couple of times and then this wonderful director named John Swanbeck

25:39.400 --> 25:41.640
who would eventually direct me in a film called The Big Kahuna.

25:42.280 --> 25:46.920
But this is before that, he said to me the most incredible thing he just said,

25:48.120 --> 25:53.000
all right, what's the last line you have in this scene before you fall over and fall asleep?

25:53.000 --> 26:00.040
And I said, the last line is that last drink, the old KO. And he went, okay,

26:01.640 --> 26:07.720
I want you to think about what that line actually means and then work backwards.

26:10.040 --> 26:16.440
And so he left and I sort of was left with this, what? Like, what does that mean? How am I supposed

26:17.720 --> 26:20.760
to? And then like a couple of days went by, a couple of days went by and I thought,

26:20.760 --> 26:28.120
okay, so I said, what does that line actually mean? Well, that last drink, the old KO. KO

26:29.480 --> 26:39.400
is knockout, which is a boxing term. It's the only boxing term the writer uses in the play.

26:40.040 --> 26:48.440
And then I went back and I realized my friend was so smart and so incredible to have said,

26:48.440 --> 26:53.480
ask a question you haven't thought of asking yet. I realized that the playwright wrote

26:54.040 --> 27:00.840
the last round, the eighth round between these two brothers, and it was a fight, physical as

27:00.840 --> 27:05.320
well as emotional. And when I brought that into the rehearsal room to the directors doing that play,

27:06.440 --> 27:12.040
he liked that idea. And we staged that scene as if it was the eighth round, although the audience

27:12.040 --> 27:18.600
wouldn't have known that. But just what I loved about that was that somebody said to me,

27:20.360 --> 27:24.200
ask yourself a question you haven't asked yourself yet. What does that line mean and

27:24.200 --> 27:31.640
then work backwards? What is that like a catalyst for thinking deeply about what is

27:31.640 --> 27:36.360
magical about this play, this story, this narrative? That's what that is, like thinking

27:36.360 --> 27:41.400
backwards, that's what that does? Yeah. But also because it's this incredible,

27:43.240 --> 27:47.320
why didn't I think to ask that question myself? That's what you have directors for, that's what

27:47.320 --> 27:53.960
you have. So many places where ideas can come from. But that just illustrates that even though in

27:53.960 --> 27:59.880
my brain I go, I always like to work backwards. I missed it in that one and I'm very grateful to

28:00.760 --> 28:07.640
to my friend for having pushed me into being able to realize what that meant and

28:08.600 --> 28:16.120
to ask the interesting question. I like the poetry and the humility of I'm just a series

28:16.120 --> 28:23.800
of collars in someone else's painting. That was a good line. That said, you've talked about

28:23.800 --> 28:28.920
improvisation. You said that it's all about the ability to do it again and again and again and

28:28.920 --> 28:35.080
yet never make it the same. And you also just said that you're trying to stay true to the text.

28:35.800 --> 28:42.520
So where's the room for the improvisation? That it's never the same? Well, there's two

28:42.520 --> 28:50.520
slightly different contexts, I think. One is in the rehearsal room, improvisation can be a wonderful

28:50.520 --> 28:57.880
device. I mean, Sam Mendes, for example, will start, he'll start a scene and he does this wonderful

28:57.880 --> 29:05.000
thing. He brings rugs and he brings chairs and sofas in and he says, well, let's put two chairs

29:05.000 --> 29:09.480
here and here. You guys, let's start in these chairs far apart from each other. Let's see what

29:09.480 --> 29:13.720
happens with the scene if you're that far apart. And so we'll do the scene that way and then he

29:13.720 --> 29:19.560
goes, okay, let's bring a rug in and let's bring these chairs much closer and let's see what happens

29:19.560 --> 29:27.160
if the space between you is. And so then you try it that way. And then it's a little harder in

29:27.160 --> 29:36.680
Shakespeare to improv. But in any situation where you want to try and see where could a scene go,

29:36.680 --> 29:40.440
where would the scene go if I didn't make that choice? Where would the scene go if I made this

29:40.440 --> 29:45.640
choice? Where would the scene go if I didn't say that or I said something else? So that's how improv

29:45.640 --> 30:01.320
can be a valuable process to learn about limits and boundaries and what's going on with a character

30:01.320 --> 30:09.000
that somehow you discover in trying something that isn't on the page. Then there's the different

30:09.000 --> 30:14.680
thing which is the trying to make it fresh and trying to make it new. And that is really a

30:14.680 --> 30:27.080
reference to theater. I'll put it to you this way. Anybody loves sports, right? So you go and you

30:27.080 --> 30:34.280
watch on a pitch, you watch on a tennis game, you watch basketball, you watch football. Yeah,

30:34.280 --> 30:39.320
the rules are the same. But it's a different game every time you're out on that court or on that field.

30:40.200 --> 30:54.600
It's no different in theater. Yes, it's the same lines. Maybe even blocking is similar. But what's

30:54.600 --> 31:04.600
different is attack, intention, how you are growing in a role and watching your fellow actors grow in

31:05.560 --> 31:11.960
theirs and how every night it's a new audience and they're reacting differently. And you literally,

31:12.840 --> 31:23.640
where you can go from week one of performances in a play to week 12 is extraordinary. And the

31:23.640 --> 31:31.480
difference between theater and film is that no matter how good someone might think you are in a

31:31.560 --> 31:40.120
movie, you'll never be any better. It's frozen. Whereas I can be better tomorrow night than I

31:40.120 --> 31:49.880
was tonight. I can be better in a week than I was tonight. It is a living, breathing, shifting,

31:49.880 --> 31:58.040
changing, growing thing every single day. But also in theater, there's no safety net. If you fuck it up,

31:59.000 --> 32:03.480
everybody gets to see you do that. And if you start giggling on stage, everyone gets to see you

32:03.480 --> 32:12.680
do that too, which I am very guilty of. I mean, there is something of a seduction of an audience

32:12.680 --> 32:20.040
in theater even more intense than there is when you're talking about film. I got a chance to watch

32:20.040 --> 32:26.280
the documentary now in the wings on a world stage, which is behind the scenes of you mentioned

32:27.240 --> 32:31.880
you teaming up with Sam Mendes in 2011 to stage Richard III,

32:34.040 --> 32:37.080
a play by William Shakespeare. I was also surprised to learn

32:38.120 --> 32:43.960
you haven't really done much Shakespeare, or at least you said that in the movie. But there's

32:43.960 --> 32:48.760
a lot of interesting behind the scenes stuff there. First of all, the camaraderie of everybody,

32:48.760 --> 32:53.640
how like the bond theater creates, especially when you're traveling.

32:54.680 --> 32:58.840
But the another interesting thing you mentioned with the chairs of Sam Mendes trying different

32:58.840 --> 33:04.120
stuff. It seemed like everybody was really open to trying stuff, embarrassing themselves,

33:04.120 --> 33:12.280
taking risks, all that. I suppose that's part of acting in general, but theater especially.

33:12.280 --> 33:16.280
Just take risks. It's okay to embarrass a shit out of yourself, including the director.

33:17.240 --> 33:25.480
And it's also because you become a family. It's unlike a movie where I might have a scene with

33:25.480 --> 33:29.240
so and so on this day and then another scene with them in a week and a half,

33:29.240 --> 33:34.040
and then that's the only scenes we have in the whole movie together. Every single day

33:35.160 --> 33:40.680
when you show up in the rehearsal room, it's the whole company. You're all up for it every day.

33:40.760 --> 33:49.480
You're learning, you're growing, you're trying, and there is an incredible trust that happens.

33:50.520 --> 33:55.720
And I was of course fortunate that some of the things I learned and observed about

33:57.960 --> 34:01.880
being a part of that family, being included in that family and being a part of creating that

34:01.880 --> 34:08.360
family, I was able to observe from people like Jack Lemmon who led many companies that I was

34:08.360 --> 34:15.400
fortunate to work in and be a part of. There's also a sad moment where at the end,

34:15.400 --> 34:20.280
everybody is really sad to say goodbye because you do form a family and then it's over.

34:21.880 --> 34:25.000
I guess somebody said that that's just part of theater. It's like,

34:26.120 --> 34:29.080
I mean, they should kind of assume goodbye and that this is it.

34:30.200 --> 34:35.000
Yeah, and also there are sometimes when like six months later, I'll wake up

34:35.080 --> 34:39.160
middle of the night and I'll go, that's how to play that scene.

34:41.560 --> 34:44.280
Oh God, I just finally figured it out.

34:45.640 --> 34:50.040
So maybe you could speak a little bit more to that. What's the difference between film acting and

34:50.040 --> 34:55.400
live theater acting? I don't really think there is any. I think there's just,

34:57.640 --> 35:03.320
you eventually learn about yourself on film, you know, when I first did like my first

35:03.560 --> 35:10.840
episode of The Equalizer, you know, it's just horrible. It's just so bad,

35:11.880 --> 35:17.160
but I didn't know about myself. I didn't slowly begin to learn about yourself, but

35:18.280 --> 35:23.960
I think good acting is good acting. And I think that, you know, if a camera's right here, you

35:23.960 --> 35:30.200
know that your front row is also your back row. You just don't have to do so much.

35:30.200 --> 35:39.000
There is in theater a particular kind of energy, almost like an athlete,

35:39.560 --> 35:45.960
that you have to have vocally to be able to get up seven performances a week and never lose your

35:45.960 --> 35:49.480
voice and always be there and always be alive and always be doing the best work you can,

35:50.040 --> 35:53.880
that you just don't require in film. You know, you don't have to have the same,

35:54.120 --> 36:03.640
it just doesn't require the same kind of stamina that doing a play does.

36:04.360 --> 36:09.640
It just feels like also in theater, you have to become the character more intensely because

36:10.600 --> 36:14.440
you can't take a break. You can't take a bathroom break. You're like on stage.

36:15.000 --> 36:19.400
There's no, this is you. Yeah, but you have no idea what's going on on stage with the actors.

36:19.400 --> 36:26.440
I mean, I have literally laughed through speeches that I had to give because

36:26.440 --> 36:31.400
my fellow actors were putting carrots up their nose or broccoli in their ears or doing whatever

36:31.400 --> 36:35.960
they were doing to make me laugh. So they're just having fun. They're having the time of their life.

36:35.960 --> 36:41.640
And by the way, Judy Dench is the worst giggler of all. I mean, they had to bring the curtain down

36:41.640 --> 36:47.160
on her and Maggie Smith because they were laughing so hard, they could not continue the play.

36:47.160 --> 36:50.760
So even when you're doing like a dramatic monologue still, they're still fucking with you.

36:50.760 --> 36:56.920
There's stuff. Okay, that's great. That's good to know. You also said an interesting line that

36:56.920 --> 37:09.560
improvisation helps you learn about the character. Can you explain that? So like through maybe playing

37:09.560 --> 37:15.480
with the different ways of saying the words or the different ways to bring the words to life,

37:16.040 --> 37:19.640
you get to learn about yourself, about the character you're playing.

37:19.640 --> 37:29.320
It can be helpful. But improv is, I'm such a big believer in the writing and in serving the writing

37:29.320 --> 37:36.280
and doing the words the writer wrote. That improv for me, unless you're just doing like

37:36.280 --> 37:42.600
comedy and you know, like, I mean, I love improv and in comedy, it's brilliant. So much fun to

37:42.600 --> 37:48.760
watch people just come up with something right there. But that's where you're looking for laughs

37:48.760 --> 37:56.920
and you're specifically in a little scene that's being created. But I think improv has had value.

37:59.640 --> 38:09.720
But I have not experienced it as much in doing plays as I have sometimes in doing film where

38:10.040 --> 38:15.320
you'll start off rehearsing and a director may say, let's just go off book and see what happens.

38:15.960 --> 38:21.800
And I've had moments in film where someone went off book and it was terrifying.

38:25.000 --> 38:27.480
There was a scene I had in Glen Gary Glen Ross

38:30.040 --> 38:37.640
where the character I play has fucked something up, just screwed something up and Pacino is livid.

38:37.960 --> 38:45.720
And so we had the scene where Al is walking like this and the camera is moving with him

38:46.680 --> 38:56.120
and he is chewing me a new asshole. And in the middle of the take Al starts talking about me.

38:58.280 --> 39:05.880
Oh, Kevin, you don't think we know how you got this job? You don't think we know

39:05.880 --> 39:11.080
who's dick you've been sucking on to get this part in this movie? And I'm now,

39:12.600 --> 39:19.400
I'm literally like, I don't know what the hell is happening, but I'm reacting.

39:21.240 --> 39:28.760
We got to the end of that take. Al walked up to me and went, oh, that was so good. Oh my god,

39:28.760 --> 39:34.360
that was so good. Just so you know, the sound, I asked them not to record. So you have no dialogue.

39:34.360 --> 39:41.480
So it's just me. Oh, that was so good. You look like a car wreck. And I was like, yeah.

39:43.240 --> 39:50.680
And it was actually an incredibly generous thing that he gave me so that I would react.

39:51.720 --> 39:58.520
Oh, wow. Did they use that shot? Because you were in the shot. It was my close-up.

39:58.760 --> 40:03.000
Yeah. Yeah. And yeah, that's the take. That was an intense, right? I mean,

40:03.000 --> 40:08.520
what was it like if we can just linger on that, just that intense scene with Al Pacino?

40:10.040 --> 40:14.920
Well, he's the reason I got the movie. A lot of people might think because Jack was in the film

40:14.920 --> 40:19.480
that he had something to do with it. But actually, I was doing a play called Lost in Yonkers on

40:19.480 --> 40:24.440
Broadway. And we had the same dresser who worked with him, a girl named Laura. It was wonderful.

40:25.400 --> 40:33.160
Laura Beattie. And she told Al that he should come and see this play because she wanted to see

40:33.160 --> 40:40.040
me in this play. I was playing this gangster's fun, fun, fun part. So I didn't know Pacino came

40:40.040 --> 40:45.160
on some night and saw this play. And then like three days later, I got a call to come in and

40:45.160 --> 40:50.120
auditioned for this Glenn Gray, Glenn Ross, which of course I knew is a play, David Mambis play.

40:50.840 --> 40:59.400
And then I auditioned. Jamie Foley was the director who would eventually direct a bunch of House of

40:59.400 --> 41:06.440
Cards. Wonderful, wonderful guy. And I got the part. Well, I didn't quite get the part. They were

41:06.440 --> 41:11.880
going to bring together the actors that they thought they were going to give the parts to on a Saturday

41:11.880 --> 41:17.000
at Al's office. And they asked me if I would come and do a read through. And I said, who's going to

41:17.960 --> 41:22.280
be there? And they said, well, so-and-so-and-so-and-so-and-so. And Jack Lemon is flying in. And I said,

41:22.280 --> 41:27.560
don't tell Mr. Lemon that I'm doing the read through. Is that possible? And I'm like, sure.

41:28.120 --> 41:34.200
So I'll never forget this. Jack was sitting in the chair in Pacino's office doing the New

41:34.200 --> 41:39.880
York Times crossword puzzle as he did every day. And I walked in the door and he went, oh, Jesus

41:39.880 --> 41:45.640
Christ. Is it possible you could get a job without me? Jesus Christ. I'm so tired of holding up your

41:45.640 --> 41:55.080
end of it. Oh my God. Jesus Christ. So I got the job because of Pacino. And it was really one of the

41:55.080 --> 42:01.480
first major roles that I ever had in a film. And to be working with that group.

42:02.360 --> 42:09.960
Yeah, that's one of the greatest ensemble casts ever. We got Al Pacino, Jack Lemon,

42:10.760 --> 42:19.960
Alec Baldwin, Alan Arkin, Ed Harris, you, Jonathan Price. It's just incredible. And I would have to

42:19.960 --> 42:25.240
say, I mean, maybe you can comment. You've talked about how much of a mentor and a friend Jack

42:25.240 --> 42:30.040
Lemon has been. That's one of his greatest performances ever. Ever. You have a scene at

42:30.040 --> 42:35.400
the end of the movie with him. That was really powerful. Like firing on all cylinders. You're

42:36.360 --> 42:42.520
playing the stain to perfection. And he's playing desperation to perfection.

42:43.480 --> 42:48.360
What a scene. What was that like? Just like at the top of your game, the two of you. Well,

42:48.360 --> 42:54.120
by that time, we had done Long Day's Journey Tonight in the theater. We'd done a mini series

42:54.120 --> 43:01.000
called The Murder of Mary Fagan on NBC. We'd done a film called Dad, that Gary David Goldberg directed

43:01.960 --> 43:08.360
with Ted Danson. So this was the fourth time we were working together and we knew each other.

43:08.360 --> 43:15.160
We'd become, he'd become my father figure. And I don't know if you know that I originally met

43:15.160 --> 43:21.160
Jack Lemon when I was very, very young. He was doing a production at the Mark Taper

43:21.160 --> 43:26.840
Forum of a Chateau Casey play called Juno and the Peacock with Walter Matthew and Maureen Stapleton.

43:26.840 --> 43:36.360
And on a Saturday in December of 1974, my junior high school drama class went to a workshop. It was

43:36.360 --> 43:43.080
called How to Audition. And we did this workshop. Many schools in Southern California were part

43:43.080 --> 43:47.640
of this Drama Teachers Association. So we got these incredible experiences of being able to go

43:47.640 --> 43:52.680
see professional productions and be involved in these workshops or festivals. So I had to get up

43:52.680 --> 43:59.320
and do a monologue in front of Mr. Lemon when I was 13 years old. And he walked up to me at the

43:59.320 --> 44:03.640
end of that and he put his hand on my shoulder and he said, that was a touch of terrific. He said,

44:03.640 --> 44:08.200
no, everything I've been talking about, you just did. What's your name? I said, Kevin, he said,

44:08.200 --> 44:11.480
let me tell you something. When you get finished with high school, as I'm sure you're going to go

44:11.480 --> 44:15.080
on and do theater, you should go to New York and you should study to be an actor because this is

44:15.080 --> 44:24.920
what you're meant to do with your life. And he was like an idol. And 12 years later, I read in

44:24.920 --> 44:28.760
the New York Times that he was coming to Broadway to do this production of A Long Day's Journey

44:28.760 --> 44:35.880
tonight, a year and some months after I read this article, and I was like, I'm going to play Jamie in

44:35.880 --> 44:44.600
that production. And I then, with a lot of opposition, the cast and director didn't want to

44:44.600 --> 44:52.120
see me. They said that the director, Jonathan Miller, wanted movie actors to play the two sons.

44:53.960 --> 45:00.280
And ultimately, I found out that Jonathan Miller, the director, was coming to New York to do a

45:00.280 --> 45:08.680
series of lectures at Alice Tully Hall. And I went to try to figure out how I could maybe meet him.

45:09.960 --> 45:16.760
And I was sitting in that theater listening to this incredible lecture he was doing, and sitting

45:16.760 --> 45:25.160
next to me was an elderly woman. I mean, elderly, 80 something, and she was asleep.

45:25.960 --> 45:35.400
But sticking out of her handbag, which was on the floor, was an invitation to a cocktail reception

45:35.400 --> 45:44.600
on her, Dr. Jonathan Miller. And so I thought, you know, she's tired. She's probably going to go home.

45:45.000 --> 45:53.000
So I took that and walked into this cocktail reception, and ultimately went over to Dr. Miller,

45:53.000 --> 45:59.000
who was incredibly kind, and said, sit down, always very curious, what brings young people

45:59.000 --> 46:04.920
to my lectures? And I said to him, Eugene O'Neill brought me here. And he was like, what? I've always

46:04.920 --> 46:11.640
wanted to meet him. Where is he? And I told him that I'd been trying for seven months to get

46:12.040 --> 46:19.320
an audition for a long day's journey, and that his American cast directors were telling my agents

46:19.320 --> 46:24.760
that he wanted big American movie stars. And at that moment, he turned and he saw

46:25.720 --> 46:31.480
one of those cast directors who was there that night. So I knew he was going to be in New York

46:31.480 --> 46:39.240
starting auditions that week. And she was staring daggers at me. And he just got it.

46:40.200 --> 46:45.320
And he said, someone have a pen. And he took the paper and started writing. He said, listen,

46:45.320 --> 46:50.040
Kevin, there are many situations in which casting directors have a lot of say and a lot of power

46:50.040 --> 46:54.440
and a lot of leverage. And then there are other situations where they just take directors' messages.

46:54.440 --> 46:57.960
And on this one, they're taking my messages. This is where I'm staying. Make sure you people get to

46:57.960 --> 47:05.240
me. We start auditions on Thursday. And on Thursday, I had an opportunity to come in and audition

47:06.120 --> 47:14.120
for this play that I've been working on and preparing. And at the end of it, I did four scenes

47:14.120 --> 47:18.920
at the end of it. He said to me that unless someone else came in and blew him against the wall,

47:18.920 --> 47:23.960
like I had just done, as far as he was concerned, I pretty much had the part, but I couldn't tell

47:23.960 --> 47:29.320
my agents that yet because I had to come back and read with Mr. Lemon. And so three months later,

47:29.320 --> 47:37.320
in August of 1985, I found myself in a room with Jack Lemon again at 890 Broadway, which is where

47:37.320 --> 47:43.160
they rehearsed a lot of Broadway plays. And we did four scenes together and I was toppling over him.

47:43.160 --> 47:49.640
I was pushing him. I was relentless. And I'll never forget at the end of that.

47:53.320 --> 47:57.160
Lemon came over to me. He put his hand on my shoulder and he said, that would you touch it?

47:57.160 --> 48:01.080
Terrific. I never thought we'd find the rotten kid, but he's it. Jesus Christ, what the hell was that?

48:03.400 --> 48:11.480
And I ended up spending the next year of my life with that man. So it turns out he was right.

48:14.360 --> 48:21.880
Yeah. This world works in mysterious ways. It also speaks to the fact of the power of somebody

48:21.880 --> 48:27.960
you look up to giving words of encouragement, because those can just reverberate through your

48:27.960 --> 48:34.920
whole life and just make the path clear. I've always, we used to joke that if every

48:34.920 --> 48:38.440
contract came with a Jack Lemon clause, it would be a more beautiful world.

48:40.120 --> 48:46.520
Beautifully said. Jack Lemon is one of the greatest actors ever. What do you think makes him so damn good?

48:47.400 --> 48:49.400
Wow.

48:55.640 --> 49:05.480
I think he truly set out in his life to accomplish what his father said to him on his deathbed.

49:07.240 --> 49:11.080
His father was died. His father was, by the way, called the Donut King in Boston.

49:11.400 --> 49:18.600
And not in the entertainment business at all. He was literally owned a donut company. And

49:20.280 --> 49:24.280
when he was passing away, Jack said, the last thing my father said to me was,

49:25.160 --> 49:33.480
go out there and spread a little sunshine. And I truly think that's what Jack loved to do.

49:33.480 --> 49:46.040
I remember this, and I don't know if this will answer your question, but I think it's revealing

49:46.040 --> 49:53.640
about what he's able to do and what he was able to do and how that ultimately influenced what I

49:53.640 --> 49:59.960
was able to do. Sam Endes had never directed a film before American Beauty.

50:02.120 --> 50:09.640
And so what he did was he took the best elements of theater and applied them to the process. So we

50:09.640 --> 50:15.160
rehearsed it like a play in a soundstage where everything was laid out like it would be in a

50:15.160 --> 50:24.600
play and this couch will be here. And he'd sent me a couple of tapes. He'd sent me two cassette

50:24.600 --> 50:31.560
tapes, one that he'd like to call pre-Lester before he begins to move in a new direction,

50:31.560 --> 50:39.080
and then post-Lester. And they just were different songs. And then he said to me one day, and I

50:39.080 --> 50:45.240
think always thought this was brilliant of Sam to use lemon, knowing what lemon meant to me.

50:46.600 --> 50:51.640
He said, when was the last time you watched The Apartment? I said, I don't know. I mean,

50:52.200 --> 50:55.880
I love that movie so much because I want you to watch it again and then let's talk.

50:58.360 --> 51:03.480
So I went and I watched the movie again and we sat down and Sam said,

51:03.640 --> 51:13.320
what lemon does in that film is incredible because there is never a moment in the movie

51:14.200 --> 51:24.200
where we see him change. He just evolves. And he becomes the man he becomes because

51:24.200 --> 51:29.720
of the experiences that he has through the course of the film. But there's this remarkable

51:29.720 --> 51:36.680
consistency in who he becomes. And that's what I need you to do is Lester. I don't want the

51:36.680 --> 51:45.000
audience to ever see him change. I want him to evolve. And so we did some, I mean, first of all,

51:45.000 --> 51:51.320
it was just a great direction. And then second of all, we did some things that people don't know

51:51.320 --> 52:01.640
we did to aid that gradual shift of that man's character. First of all, I had to be in the

52:01.640 --> 52:06.040
best shape from the beginning of the movie because we didn't shoot it in sequence. So

52:06.840 --> 52:13.080
I was in this crazy shape. I had this wonderful trainer named Mike Torsche who just was incredible.

52:13.640 --> 52:21.880
But so what we did was in order to then show this gradual shift was I had three different

52:21.880 --> 52:30.120
hairpieces. I had three different kinds of costumes of different colors and sizes. And I had different

52:30.120 --> 52:38.520
makeup. So in the beginning, I was wearing a kind of drab, dull, slightly, you know,

52:38.520 --> 52:45.080
uninspired hairpiece. And my makeup was kind of gray and boring. And I was a little bit,

52:45.080 --> 52:49.560
there were times when I was like too much like this and Sam would go, Kevin, you look like

52:49.560 --> 52:53.640
Walter Mathau, would you please stand up a little bit? We're sort of midway through at this point.

52:54.600 --> 53:02.760
And then at a certain point, the wig changed and it had little highlights in it, a little more

53:02.760 --> 53:09.160
color, a little more, the makeup became a little, the suits got a little tighter. And then finally,

53:09.160 --> 53:16.280
a third wig that was golden highlights and sunshine and, and, you know, rosy cheeks and tight fit.

53:16.920 --> 53:20.680
And these are what we call theatrical tricks. You know, this is, this is how you,

53:21.240 --> 53:27.720
an audience doesn't even know it's happening. But it is this gradual. And I just always felt that

53:27.720 --> 53:37.480
that was such a brilliant way because he knew what I felt about Jack. And when you watch the

53:37.480 --> 53:44.520
apartment, it is extraordinary that he doesn't ever change. He just, so I'm, I'm,

53:44.520 --> 54:02.120
and in fact, I, I thanked Jack when I won the Oscar. And I, I did my thank you speech and I

54:02.120 --> 54:07.080
walked off stage and I remember I had to sit down for a moment because I didn't want to go,

54:07.080 --> 54:10.840
I didn't want to go to the press room because I wanted to see if Sam was going to win.

54:11.800 --> 54:18.840
And so I was waiting and my phone rang and it was lemon. He said, you're a son of a bitch.

54:20.040 --> 54:25.720
I said, I said, what? He goes, do you, first of all, congratulations and thanks for thanking me

54:25.720 --> 54:29.400
because, you know, God knows you couldn't have done it without me. He said, second of all,

54:29.960 --> 54:35.400
he said, you know how long it took me to win from supporting actor. I won it for Mr. Roberts and

54:35.400 --> 54:39.640
it took me like 10, 12 years to win Oscar. You did it in four, you son of a bitch.

54:41.800 --> 54:48.920
Yeah. The apartment was, I mean, it's widely considered one of the greatest movies ever.

54:50.760 --> 54:55.640
People sometimes refer to it as a comedy, which is an interesting kind of classification.

54:56.200 --> 55:02.120
I suppose that's a lesson about comedy that the best, the best comedy is the one that's

55:02.120 --> 55:06.440
basically a tragedy. Well, I mean, some people think Clockwork Orange is a comedy.

55:07.320 --> 55:11.880
And I'm not saying there are some good laughs in Clockwork Orange, but yeah, you know, it's...

55:12.760 --> 55:18.920
I mean, yeah. What's that line between comedy and tragedy for you?

55:23.080 --> 55:31.640
Well, if it's a line, it's a line I cross all the time because I've tried always to find the humor

55:32.440 --> 55:42.760
unexpected sometimes, maybe inappropriate sometimes, maybe shocking, but I've tried and

55:42.760 --> 55:51.640
I think almost every dramatic role I've had to have a sense of humor and to be able to bring

55:52.520 --> 55:58.760
that along with everything else that is serious. Because frankly,

55:58.840 --> 56:06.200
that's how we deal with stuff in life, you know? I think Sam Mendes actually said in the

56:06.200 --> 56:14.440
now documentary something like, with great theater, with great stories, you find humor

56:15.080 --> 56:21.480
on the journey to the heart of darkness, something like this. Very poetic, it stood out to me.

56:21.480 --> 56:26.120
Yeah, I'm sorry, I can't be that poetic. I'm very sorry. But it's true. I mean,

56:27.080 --> 56:30.440
the people I've interacted in this world have been to a war zone and

56:32.440 --> 56:38.040
the ones who have lost the most and have suffered the most are usually the ones who are able to

56:40.040 --> 56:45.880
make jokes the quickest and the jokes are often dark and absurd and cost every single line,

56:46.440 --> 56:50.440
no political correctness, all of that. Sure. Well, I mean, you know, it's like

56:51.400 --> 56:57.080
the Great Mary Tyler Moore show where they can't stop giggling at the clown's funeral. I mean,

56:57.080 --> 57:03.640
it's just one of the great episodes ever. Giggling at a funeral is as bad as farting at a funeral

57:03.640 --> 57:13.000
and I'm sure that there's some people who've done both. Oh, man. So you mentioned American beauty

57:13.320 --> 57:22.280
and the idea of not changing but evolving. That's really interesting because that movie is about

57:22.920 --> 57:29.320
like finding yourself. So it's a philosophically profound movie. It's about various characters

57:29.320 --> 57:38.120
in their own ways, finding their own identity in a world where maybe a system, a materialistic

57:38.120 --> 57:43.400
system that wants you to be like everyone else. And so, I mean, Lester just really transforms

57:43.400 --> 57:48.840
himself throughout the movie and you're saying the challenge there is to still be the same human

57:48.840 --> 58:01.960
being fundamentally. Yeah, and I also think that the film was powerful because you had three

58:02.920 --> 58:12.200
very honest and genuine portrayal of young people and then you had Lester behaving like a young

58:12.200 --> 58:23.720
person, doing things that were unexpected. And I think that the honesty with which it dealt with

58:23.720 --> 58:29.240
those issues that those teenagers were going through and the honesty with which it dealt with

58:29.240 --> 58:37.720
what Lester was going through, I think are some of the reasons why the film had the response that

58:37.720 --> 58:46.120
it did from so many people. I mean, I used to get stopped and someone would say to me,

58:47.240 --> 58:52.920
when I first saw American beauty, I was married. And the second time I saw it, I wasn't.

58:53.080 --> 58:59.720
And I was like, well, we weren't trying to increase the divorce rate. It wasn't our intention, but

59:00.520 --> 59:11.960
it is interesting how so many people have those kinds of crazy fantasies. And what I

59:13.480 --> 59:17.960
admired so much about who Lester was as a person, why I wanted to play him is because in the end,

59:18.760 --> 59:24.680
he makes the right decision. I think a lot of people live lives of quiet desperation

59:26.440 --> 59:36.280
in a job they don't like. In a marriage they're unhappy in and to see somebody

59:37.560 --> 59:44.440
living that life and then saying, fuck it in every way possible. And not just in a cynical way,

59:44.440 --> 59:51.640
but in a way that opens Lester up to see the beauty in the world. That's the beauty in American

59:51.640 --> 59:58.280
beauty. Well, you may have to blackmail your boss to get there, but you know. And in that,

59:58.280 --> 01:00:07.080
there's a bunch of humor also. In the anger and the absurdity of taking a stand against the

01:00:07.080 --> 01:00:14.760
conformity of life, there's this humor. And I read somewhere that the scene, the dinner scene,

01:00:14.760 --> 01:00:24.280
which is kind of play-like, where Lester slams the plate against the wall, was improvised by you,

01:00:25.960 --> 01:00:31.400
the slamming of the plate against the wall. No. No. Absolutely. The internet lies once again.

01:00:31.480 --> 01:00:40.600
Absolutely written and directed. Can't take credit for that.

01:00:40.600 --> 01:00:45.880
The plate. Okay. Well, that was a genius interaction there. There's something about the

01:00:45.880 --> 01:00:51.240
dinner table and losing your shit at the dinner table. Having a fight and losing your shit at the

01:00:51.240 --> 01:00:59.720
dinner table. Where else? Yellowstone was another situation where there's a family

01:01:00.280 --> 01:01:05.080
at the dinner table and then one of them says, fucking, I'm not eating this anymore and I'm

01:01:05.080 --> 01:01:10.840
going to create a scene. Right. It's a beautiful kind of environment for dramatic scenes.

01:01:10.840 --> 01:01:17.400
Or Nicholson in The Shining. There's some family scenes gone awry in that movie.

01:01:17.400 --> 01:01:20.600
The contrast between you and Annette Benning in that scene

01:01:23.080 --> 01:01:29.000
creates the genius of that scene. So how much of acting is the dance between two actors?

01:01:30.280 --> 01:01:41.720
Well, with Annette, I just adored working with her. And we were the two actors that Sam wanted

01:01:41.720 --> 01:01:48.680
from the very beginning, much against the will of the higher ups who wanted other actors to

01:01:48.680 --> 01:01:59.320
play those roles. But I've known Annette since we did a screen test together from Milos Forman

01:01:59.960 --> 01:02:05.640
for a film he did of the Les Léves-en-Dangerous movie. It was a different film from that one,

01:02:05.640 --> 01:02:11.960
but it was the same story. And I've always thought she is just remarkable. And I think that

01:02:12.920 --> 01:02:20.840
the work she did in that film, the relationship that we were able to build,

01:02:23.720 --> 01:02:29.320
for me, the saddest part of that success was that she didn't win the Oscar,

01:02:30.120 --> 01:02:37.240
and I felt she should have. What kind of interesting direction did you get from Sam

01:02:37.320 --> 01:02:44.280
and how you approached playing Lester and how to take on the different scenes?

01:02:44.280 --> 01:02:46.680
There's a lot of just brilliant scenes in that movie.

01:02:46.680 --> 01:02:56.040
Well, I'll share with you a story that most people don't know, which is our first two days

01:02:56.040 --> 01:03:03.480
of shooting were in Smiley's, the place where I get a job in a fast food place.

01:03:03.560 --> 01:03:07.640
Yeah, it's a burger joint. And I guess it was like maybe

01:03:09.080 --> 01:03:15.800
the third day or the fourth day of shooting, we'd now done that. And I said to Sam,

01:03:16.600 --> 01:03:22.600
so how are the dailies? How do they look? He goes, which ones? I said, well, the first

01:03:23.320 --> 01:03:30.280
Smiley's. He goes, oh, they're shit. And I went, yeah, no, how were they? He goes, no, they're

01:03:30.280 --> 01:03:37.960
shit. I hate them. I hate everything about them. I hate the costumes. I hate the location.

01:03:37.960 --> 01:03:46.360
I hate that you're inside. I hate the way you acted. I hate everything but the script.

01:03:47.320 --> 01:03:50.760
So I've gone back to the studio and asked them if we can reshoot the first two days.

01:03:51.560 --> 01:04:01.480
And it was like, Sam, this is your very first movie. You're going back to Steven Spielberg

01:04:01.480 --> 01:04:09.960
and saying, I need to reshoot the first two days entirely. Yeah. And that's exactly what we did.

01:04:10.840 --> 01:04:16.600
A couple of weeks later, they decided that it was now a drive through because Annette and

01:04:16.600 --> 01:04:23.160
Peter Galler used to come into the place and ordered from the counter. Now, Sam decided,

01:04:23.160 --> 01:04:26.440
it has to be a drive through. You have to be in the window of the drive through,

01:04:26.440 --> 01:04:31.160
change the costumes, and we reshot those first two days. And Sam said,

01:04:33.160 --> 01:04:40.040
it was actually a moment of incredible confidence because he said the worst thing that could

01:04:40.040 --> 01:04:47.160
possibly have happened happened in my first two days. And after that, I was like, I know what

01:04:47.160 --> 01:04:52.200
I'm doing and I knew I had to reshoot it and it was absolutely right. And I guess that's what a

01:04:52.200 --> 01:04:58.520
great director must do is have the guts in that moment to reshoot everything. That's a pretty

01:04:58.520 --> 01:05:05.560
gutsy move. Two other little things to share with you about Sam, but the way he is, you wouldn't

01:05:05.560 --> 01:05:16.840
know it, but the original script opened and closed with a trial. Ricky was accused of Lester's murder.

01:05:17.880 --> 01:05:21.720
And the movie was bookended by this trial. It's a very different movie.

01:05:21.720 --> 01:05:32.440
Which they shot the entire trial for weeks. And I used to fly in my dreams.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:39.080
You know those opening shots over the neighborhood? I used to come into those shots in my bathrobe

01:05:40.280 --> 01:05:46.360
flying. And then when I hit the ground and the newspaper was thrown at me by the newspaper guy

01:05:46.360 --> 01:05:52.840
and I caught it, the alarm would go off and I'd wake up in bed. I spent five days being hung by

01:05:52.840 --> 01:05:59.640
wires and filming these sequences of flying through my dreams. And Sam said to me,

01:05:59.720 --> 01:06:06.760
yeah, the flying sequences are all gone and the trial is gone. And I was like, what?

01:06:08.120 --> 01:06:14.920
What are you talking about? And here's my other little favorite story about Sam and that.

01:06:15.480 --> 01:06:21.480
When we were shooting in the valley, one of those places I flew, this was an indoor set.

01:06:22.040 --> 01:06:29.800
Sam said to me in the morning, hey, at lunch, I just want to record a guide track of all the

01:06:29.800 --> 01:06:34.600
dialogue, all of your narration, because they just needed an editing as a guide. And I said, sure.

01:06:35.160 --> 01:06:40.120
So I remember we came outside of this in this hallway where I had a dressing room in this

01:06:40.120 --> 01:06:47.960
little studio we were in. And Sam had like a cassette tape recorder and like a little microphone.

01:06:48.920 --> 01:06:56.600
And we put it on the floor and he pushed record. And I read the entire narration.

01:06:59.160 --> 01:07:08.440
And I never did it again. That's the narration in the movie. Because Sam said, when he listened to it,

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:15.320
I wasn't trying to do anything. He said, you had no idea where these things were going,

01:07:15.400 --> 01:07:19.480
where they were going to be placed, what they were going to mean. You just read it so

01:07:20.360 --> 01:07:28.040
innocently, so purely, so directly that I knew if I brought you into a studio and put headphones

01:07:28.040 --> 01:07:37.640
on you and had you do it again, it would change the ease with which you'd done it. And so they

01:07:37.640 --> 01:07:45.000
just fixed all of the problems that they had with this little cassette. And that is the way I did

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:52.520
it. And the only time I did it was in this little hallway. And once again, a great performance lies

01:07:52.520 --> 01:07:59.400
in being doing less. Yeah. Yeah. The innocence and the purity of less. He knew I would have

01:07:59.400 --> 01:08:06.600
come into the studio and fucked it up. Yeah. What do you think about the notion of beauty that

01:08:06.600 --> 01:08:12.120
permeates American beauty? What do you think that theme is with the roses, with the rose petals,

01:08:12.120 --> 01:08:21.960
the characters that are living this mundane existence slowly opening their eyes up to what is

01:08:21.960 --> 01:08:27.720
beautiful in life? See, it's funny. I don't think of the roses and I don't think of her body and

01:08:27.720 --> 01:08:38.680
the poster and I don't think of those things as the beauty. I think of the bag. I think that

01:08:39.080 --> 01:08:48.440
there are things we miss that are right in front of us that are truly beautiful.

01:08:50.520 --> 01:08:55.240
The little things, the simple things. Yeah. And in fact, I'll even tell you something that I always

01:08:55.240 --> 01:09:04.280
thought was so incredible. When we shot the scenes in the office where Lester worked,

01:09:04.280 --> 01:09:08.120
the job he hated, there was a bulletin board behind me on a wall.

01:09:11.480 --> 01:09:18.760
And someone who was watching a cut or early dailies who was in the marketing department

01:09:20.600 --> 01:09:27.880
saw that someone had cut out a little piece of paper and stuck it and it said, look closer.

01:09:28.120 --> 01:09:35.240
And they presented that to Sam as the idea of what that should, that could go on the poster.

01:09:35.960 --> 01:09:43.880
The idea of looking closer was such a brilliant idea, but it wasn't, I mean, it wasn't like,

01:09:43.880 --> 01:09:48.520
it wasn't in the script. It was just on a wall behind me and someone happened to

01:09:49.160 --> 01:09:55.080
zoom in on it and see it and thought, that's what this movie's about. This movie's about

01:09:55.160 --> 01:10:03.640
taking the time to look closer. And I think that in itself is just beautiful.

01:10:04.680 --> 01:10:10.600
Mortality also permeates the film. It starts with acknowledging that death is on the way,

01:10:11.160 --> 01:10:21.080
that Lester's time is finite. You ever think about your own death? Yeah. Scared of it?

01:10:25.640 --> 01:10:29.640
When I was at my lowest point, yes, it scared me.

01:10:30.840 --> 01:10:37.160
What does that fear look like? What's the nature of the fear? What are you afraid of?

01:10:41.240 --> 01:10:42.280
That there's no way out.

01:10:45.240 --> 01:10:46.280
That there's no answer.

01:10:47.080 --> 01:10:54.600
That nothing makes sense.

01:10:57.960 --> 01:11:05.320
See, the interesting thing about Lester is facing the same fear. He seemed to be somehow liberated

01:11:06.760 --> 01:11:10.040
and accepted everything and then saw the beauty of it.

01:11:10.040 --> 01:11:17.320
Because he got there. He was given the opportunity to reinvent himself and to

01:11:21.160 --> 01:11:30.120
try things he'd never tried, to ask questions he'd never asked, to trust his instincts

01:11:30.920 --> 01:11:40.440
and to become the best version of himself he could become. And so Dick Van Dyke, who has

01:11:40.440 --> 01:11:49.000
become an extraordinary friend of mine, Dick is 98 years old. And he says, you know, if I'd known

01:11:49.000 --> 01:11:55.400
I was going to live this long, I would have taken better care of myself. When I spend time with him,

01:11:56.360 --> 01:12:03.400
I'm just moved by every day, you know, he gets up and he goes, it's a good day, I woke up.

01:12:04.280 --> 01:12:16.280
And I learn a lot about, I have a different feeling about death now than I did seven years ago.

01:12:17.240 --> 01:12:29.000
And I'm on the path to being able to be in a place where

01:12:30.760 --> 01:12:36.200
I've resolved the things I needed to resolve and won't probably get to all of it in my lifetime,

01:12:36.200 --> 01:12:43.880
but I certainly would like to be at a place where if I were to drop dead tomorrow,

01:12:43.880 --> 01:12:49.880
it would have been an amazing life. So Lester got there, it sounds like Dick Van Dyke got there,

01:12:49.880 --> 01:12:57.480
he tried to get there. Sure. You said you feared death at your lowest point. What was the lowest

01:12:57.480 --> 01:13:08.680
point? It was November 1st of 2017, and then Thanksgiving Day of that same year.

